f the West of England</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/J001139/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>As British cities become increasingly diverse, growing demands on shrinking resources are inevitably leading to community tension and conflict - especially in the most deprived areas in the country. Hen Wilkinson set up Community Resolve in Bristol in 2002 with a particular interest in how different cultural groups operate when tensions arise. The organisation promotes skills development as well as facilitating open dialogue, discussion and constructive community conflict approaches. Community Resolve is now acknowledged regionally as a leading community relations organisation and works closely with local authority departments, police and schools. Its innovative approach is recognised nationally ? several of its interventions and pilots have been picked up as ?best practice? by central government departments including the Home Office, Cabinet Office, Department of Children, Schools and Families and Department of Communities and Local Government.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>The Centre for Psycho-Social Studies at UWE and Community Resolve have worked closely together around research, training and education for several years. The ESRC Third Sector Fellowship will enable Hen to extract the learning from the last decade of work with Community Resolve and UWE, and to share the findings with national networks looking at issues of community conflict, cohesion and resilience.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2012-12-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2012-01-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>18884</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>9964662B-C077-4032-919B-42A84DB31392</gtr:id><gtr:title>Fairness and the Politics of Resentment</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Journal of Social Policy</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/10911e1532a7c17059efdf728de2aaa4"><gtr:id>10911e1532a7c17059efdf728de2aaa4</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>HOGGETT P</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2013-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>5461d6954f7a27.08496470</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication></gtr:publications><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RES">RES-173-27-0252</gtr:identifier><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">ES/J001139/1</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects>